So I think we're going
to provide a break time.

00:59:14.050 --> 00:59:15.780
But you have heard
some themes here

00:59:15.780 --> 00:59:17.920
that I just want
to reiterate-- some

00:59:17.920 --> 00:59:20.436
of the phrases of
having a master

00:59:20.436 --> 00:59:22.310
or being the general
contractor of your life.

00:59:22.310 --> 00:59:24.250
I always say have a
mission statement.

00:59:24.250 --> 00:59:28.930
And part of that
is being strategic.

00:59:28.930 --> 00:59:29.960
Time is short.

00:59:29.960 --> 00:59:32.160
And so I think a lot
of the questions,

00:59:32.160 --> 00:59:34.320
a lot of the comments
were about ways

00:59:34.320 --> 00:59:38.590
in which people try to be
strategic about their time

00:59:38.590 --> 00:59:41.850
and their energy
and their resources.

00:59:41.850 --> 00:59:45.730
Another part is, learning
to say "I don't know"

00:59:45.730 --> 00:59:48.690
is one of the hardest things
for a Harvard faculty member

00:59:48.690 --> 00:59:50.120
to say.

00:59:50.120 --> 00:59:52.950
Because we selected you.

00:59:52.950 --> 00:59:54.342
We expect you know everything.

00:59:54.342 --> 00:59:55.300
And you know something?

00:59:55.300 --> 00:59:56.050
You don't.

00:59:56.050 --> 00:59:57.812
And so whether it's
learning to say

00:59:57.812 --> 00:59:59.770
"I don't know" to a
student, when it's learning

00:59:59.770 --> 01:00:01.790
to say "I don't
know" to a colleague,

01:00:01.790 --> 01:00:04.320
when it's learning to say "I
don't know" to a colleague.

01:00:04.320 --> 01:00:05.590
"Can you give me some advice?"

01:00:05.590 --> 01:00:09.620
And then never only
ask one person.

01:00:09.620 --> 01:00:11.107
Because if you only
ask one person,

01:00:11.107 --> 01:00:13.190
you'll be convinced that
that person just gave you

01:00:13.190 --> 01:00:14.630
the right answer.

01:00:14.630 --> 01:00:17.410
And chances are
that person didn't.

01:00:17.410 --> 01:00:20.900
So learning how to ask
questions is something that

01:00:20.900 --> 01:00:23.246
has come up time and a time.

01:00:23.246 --> 01:00:24.870
And reaching outside
of your boundaries

01:00:24.870 --> 01:00:28.120
is something that we're
very interested in.

01:00:28.120 --> 01:00:30.560
I've had the pleasure reading
most of your dossiers.

01:00:30.560 --> 01:00:34.190
So a lot of the work that's
done by the people in this room

01:00:34.190 --> 01:00:36.330
increasingly is
interdisciplinary.

01:00:36.330 --> 01:00:38.490
And so learning how
to cross boundaries,

01:00:38.490 --> 01:00:41.510
but also being strategic and
not crossing so many boundaries

01:00:41.510 --> 01:00:43.980
that you're splat
on the floor and you

01:00:43.980 --> 01:00:45.880
haven't done the kinds
of strategic things

01:00:45.880 --> 01:00:48.130
that you need to be successful.

01:00:48.130 --> 01:00:50.035
And if the success
leads to tenure, great.

01:00:50.035 --> 01:00:52.160
If it doesn't, at least
you'll be true to yourself.

01:00:52.160 --> 01:00:56.940
And so being successful and
strategic and time management--

01:00:56.940 --> 01:00:58.779
I think several people
said that's probably

01:00:58.779 --> 01:00:59.820
the most important thing.

01:00:59.820 --> 01:01:01.810
Learning to say no is
about time management.

01:01:01.810 --> 01:01:04.890
Being proactive is
about time management.

01:01:04.890 --> 01:01:06.764
Instead of waiting to
see what committees

01:01:06.764 --> 01:01:09.180
you're asked to be on, think
about what the two things you

01:01:09.180 --> 01:01:10.860
want to do are, go
to your department

01:01:10.860 --> 01:01:12.760
chair or your
academic dean and say,

01:01:12.760 --> 01:01:14.460
these are the things
that interest me.

01:01:14.460 --> 01:01:15.850
They're perfectly
happy to figure out

01:01:15.850 --> 01:01:16.850
how to work around that.

01:01:16.850 --> 01:01:19.800
So instead of just waiting
for things to happen,

01:01:19.800 --> 01:01:23.680
being proactive and having
that align with your mission

01:01:23.680 --> 01:01:27.895
becomes another way to think
about being successful here.

01:01:27.895 --> 01:01:29.270
I'm going to close
it out by just

01:01:29.270 --> 01:01:30.910
